The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The states of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalisation of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in distress due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has businesses in Hungary.
This weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's economic competition officer.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the crisis in the Euro area in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so the decisions taken with regard to the Bank can in a sense be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken in the early morning of Sunday, the three states will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the property held by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis actions started a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However analysts agree to point out that with its 85 thousand employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break.
The company's shares on Friday alone decreased by 12 percent, with this being the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares decreased by more than two thirds.
Looking at the current prices of the shares, the total value of the group's capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management pushed the sharp fall of Fortis shares to the American market's insecurities in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday the shares already showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had already assured that investors had nothing to worry about, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank's clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch office in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract by viewing the data on drug purchases.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which joins the use of the data of the recipes in all cases to the approval of the given person.
The same must be in independent hands, because if not, "we trust the fox henhouse" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and compensation amount dependent on the customer's health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
They first sent the client to medical check-up and signed the contract with him knowing the outcome of the check-up.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer's identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the client.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that the level of fat in your blood is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Many versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this respect.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some medicines are multi-use, for example certain substances serve both to treat headache as well as for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk increase factor for insurance companies while the former do not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, request the patient's approval.
The authorities already force them to do this, although they were not fined for the negligence of so far.
Some companies have recently also developed the results of the laboratory tests, and linking them to the data on drug use obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and health service providers.
The bill providing for the right to the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is now before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because if not the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, despite everything, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
