Found Steve Fossett's plane the missing millionaire a year ago.
The remains of Steve Fossett's plane, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The rubble has been found on a plateau at 3000 meters altitude, in the area of the Sierra Nevada of Mammoth Lakes, in the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Wood County commissioner John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is typical of that about which Steve Fossett was flying the day of his disappearance" he said in a print conference.
The commissioner has specified that no human remains have been found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
The 63-year-old millionaire was considered dead in February.
The American office for transport safety (Ntsb) has made it known that a few hours after the sighting of the remains, a squadron of researchers has been sent that has identified the apparatus: it is typical of the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerrington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the border of Nevada, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents under the name of Fossett, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, at the sixth tempt, he had become the first Man to complete the turn of the world in a hot air balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the world turn by plane and without stopovers.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters in height, over the Andes, but with a copilot.
